  "The difference between an experiment and an observational study is:": "",
  "Observational studies are always better because they do not require ethical approval from IRBs": "",
  "Experiments are always unethical because they impose treatments on unwilling participants": "",
  "No difference exists between the two approaches; they produce identical statistical conclusions": "",
  "Experiments impose treatments on subjects; observational studies only observe without intervention": "",
  "Random assignment of treatments is what distinguishes experiments from observational studies and allows causal conclusions.": "",
  "Randomization is important because it:": "",
  "Increases bias by introducing unpredictable variation into the data collection process used": "",
  "Makes calculations easier by ensuring the numbers in the dataset are simpler to work with": "",
  "Is not important for valid inference and can be skipped without affecting the study conclusions": "",
  "Reduces bias and allows causal conclusions (in experiments) or representative sampling": "",
  "Randomization is the foundation of valid inference, whether in sampling (reducing selection bias) or experiments (enabling causal claims).": "",
  "The normal condition for proportions requires:": "",
  "np ≥ 10 AND n(1−p) ≥ 10": "",
  "np is at least 5, which is sufficient for the normal approximation to the binomial": "",
  "n is at least 30, which guarantees normality of the sampling distribution of p-hat": "",
  "p is at least 0.5, ensuring the binomial distribution is symmetric enough for approximation": "",
  "Both np and n(1−p) must be at least 10 to ensure the normal approximation to the binomial is adequate.": "",
  "A Type I error occurs when:": "",
  "The p-value is large": "",
  "We fail to reject a false H₀": "",
  "We reject H₀ when it is actually true (false positive)": "",
  "The CI is too narrow": "",
  "A Type I error is a false positive: concluding there is an effect when there truly is none.": "",
  "A Type II error occurs when:": "",
  "We reject a true null hypothesis and conclude there is an effect when there really is none": "",
  "Alpha is set too high, making the significance threshold too lenient for the given test": "",
  "The sample is too large, causing even trivially small effects to appear statistically significant": "",
  "We fail to reject H₀ when it is actually false (false negative)": "",
  "A Type II error is a false negative: failing to detect a real effect that actually exists.": "",
  "Increasing sample size:": "",
  "Has no effect on inference": "",
  "Decreases the margin of error and increases the power of the test": "",
  "Increases bias": "",
  "Increases Type I error rate": "",
  "Larger samples give more precise estimates (smaller margin of error) and greater ability to detect real effects (higher power).": "",
  "To earn full credit on a free-response question, you must:": "",
  "Only state the conclusion": "",
  "Just write the final answer": "",
  "State hypotheses, check conditions, show calculations, and conclude in context": "",
  "Only compute the test statistic": "",
  "Each component (hypotheses, conditions, mechanics, conclusion in context) earns points on the AP rubric.": "",
  "Stratified sampling involves:": "",
  "Sampling only the most convenient individuals": "",
  "Using only one group": "",
  "Dividing the population into strata and sampling from each to improve representation": "",
  "Always biased sampling": "",
  "Stratification ensures all important subgroups are represented proportionally, often reducing variability.": "",
  "On the AP exam, eliminating wrong answers on multiple choice questions:": "",
  "Is a waste of time because you either know the answer or you do not on a timed examination": "",
  "Can improve your score even when you are not sure of the correct answer": "",
  "Is considered cheating and may result in having your exam score invalidated by the College Board": "",
  "Reduces your score because guessing incorrectly after elimination still carries a penalty": "",
  "Process of elimination is a valuable test-taking strategy, especially since there is no penalty for guessing on the AP exam.": "",
  "What does 'interpret the confidence level' mean on the AP exam?": "",
  "We are C% sure the sample statistic is correct": "",
  "C% of the data falls in the interval": "",
  "If we repeated this process many times, about C% of the resulting intervals would capture the true parameter": "",
  "The parameter is definitely in the interval": "",
  "The confidence level refers to the long-run capture rate of the procedure, not the probability that any single interval contains the parameter.": "",
  "What is the purpose of a random sample?": "",
  "To guarantee perfect results": "",
  "To ensure a large sample size": "",
  "To avoid the need for statistics": "",
  "To reduce bias and allow generalization from the sample to the population": "",
  "Random sampling is the basis for extending conclusions from a sample to the broader population.": "",
  "What does 'statistical power' refer to?": "",
  "The probability of a Type I error": "",
  "The confidence level of an interval": "",
  "The probability of correctly rejecting H₀ when it is false (detecting a real effect)": "",
  "The p-value of the test": "",
  "Power = 1 − P(Type II error). Higher power means a greater chance of detecting a true effect when one exists.": "",
  "What does 'degrees of freedom' represent conceptually?": "",
  "The sample size, which is always equal to the degrees of freedom for every statistical test": "",
  "The number of variables in the dataset being analyzed regardless of how many are being estimated": "",
  "The significance level chosen for the hypothesis test, typically set at 0.05 by convention": "",
  "The number of independent pieces of information available for estimating a parameter": "",
  "Degrees of freedom count the independent pieces of information remaining after estimating parameters, and they determine the shape of the t or chi-square distribution used.": "",
  "What is the difference between statistical significance and practical significance?": "",
  "Statistical significance means the result is unlikely due to chance; practical significance means the effect is large enough to matter in the real world": "",
  "Practical significance requires a larger p-value to demonstrate that the effect matters in real life": "",
  "They mean the same thing and can be used interchangeably in any statistical analysis discussion": "",
  "Statistical significance is more important than practical significance because p-values are objective measures": "",
  "A result can be statistically significant (small p-value) but practically insignificant (trivially small effect), especially with very large samples.": "",
  "What does the Welch approximation provide for a two-sample t-test?": "",
  "The pooled proportion used when population variances are assumed to be equal across groups": "",
  "An estimated degrees of freedom when population variances are unequal": "",
  "The chi-square statistic for testing independence between two categorical variables in a table": "",
  "The exact p-value computed directly from the t-distribution without any need for approximation": "",
  "The Welch approximation calculates degrees of freedom for two-sample t-tests without assuming equal population variances.": "",
  "What does 'lurking variable' mean?": "",
  "The explanatory variable that is deliberately manipulated or observed in the study design": "",
  "The response variable that is being measured as the outcome of the study being conducted": "",
  "A variable not included in the study that may affect the relationship between the variables being studied": "",
  "A variable that is included in the model and appears as a predictor in the regression equation": "",
  "A lurking variable is an unmeasured variable that influences both the explanatory and response variables, potentially creating a misleading association.": "",
