  "AP Statistics teaches critical thinking about data that applies to every field and to everyday decision-making.": "",
  "A researcher wants to test whether a new fertilizer increases crop yield. She randomly assigns 60 plots to either the new fertilizer (n₁ = 30, mean = 52.3 bushels, s₁ = 6.1) or the standard fertilizer (n₂ = 30, mean = 48.7 bushels, s₂ = 5.8). She performs a two-sample t-test and gets t = 2.33 with p = 0.023. At α = 0.05, what is the correct conclusion?": "",
  "The test is invalid because the sample sizes are equal, which prevents a fair comparison between groups": "",
  "Fail to reject the null hypothesis; there is no significant difference between the fertilizer groups": "",
  "Reject the null hypothesis because t is greater than 2, which is always the threshold for significance": "",
  "Since p = 0.023 < 0.05, reject H₀. There is convincing evidence that the new fertilizer produces a higher mean crop yield than the standard fertilizer.": "",
  "p = 0.023 < α = 0.05, so we reject H₀. Because this was a randomized experiment, we can conclude the new fertilizer caused higher yields.": "",
  "A polling organization surveys 1,200 adults and finds that 54% approve of a new policy. They compute a 95% CI of (0.512, 0.568). A politician claims that a majority (more than 50%) supports the policy. Does the CI support this claim?": "",
  "Yes, because 54% is greater than 50% in the sample, which directly proves majority approval": "",
  "No, because the confidence interval includes values below 54%, which indicates uncertainty in the estimate": "",
  "Yes, because the entire 95% CI (0.512 to 0.568) is above 0.50, providing convincing evidence that more than 50% of the population supports the policy": "",
  "No, because we need a 99% confidence interval to be sure of any conclusion about the true proportion": "",
  "Since the entire interval (0.512 to 0.568) lies above 0.50, we have evidence at the 95% confidence level that the true population proportion exceeds 50%.": "",
  "A doctor conducts a study on 100 patients with two treatments. She finds p = 0.042 for the two-sample t-test. However, the mean difference is only 0.3 points on a 100-point pain scale. A colleague asks about practical significance. What is the best response?": "",
  "The result is both statistically and practically significant because p is less than the alpha level of 0.05": "",
  "The result is not significant at all because p = 0.042 is very close to the 0.05 threshold for rejection": "",
  "Practical significance is irrelevant in medicine because any detectable effect warrants changing treatment": "",
  "While the result is statistically significant (p = 0.042 < 0.05), the mean difference of 0.3 on a 100-point scale is likely too small to be clinically meaningful, illustrating the difference between statistical and practical significance": "",
  "With large samples, even trivially small effects can be statistically significant. Practical significance considers whether the effect is large enough to matter in the real world.": "",
  "A chi-square test of independence is performed on a 3×4 contingency table with 600 observations. The test yields χ² = 15.8. What are the degrees of freedom, and is the result significant at α = 0.05 given that the critical value for df = 6 at α = 0.05 is 12.59?": "",
  "df = 7; significant": "",
  "df = 12; not significant": "",
  "df = 6; since χ² = 15.8 > 12.59, the result is significant at α = 0.05": "",
  "df = 6; not significant because 15.8 < 600": "",
  "df = (rows − 1)(cols − 1) = (3 − 1)(4 − 1) = 2 × 3 = 6. Since χ² = 15.8 exceeds the critical value of 12.59, we reject H₀ and conclude the variables are associated.": "",
  "A regression analysis of study hours (x) vs. exam score (y) yields ŷ = 45 + 4.2x, r = 0.82, r² = 0.6724. A student who studied 10 hours scored 78. What is the residual for this student?": "",
  "9.0": "",
  "−12.0": "",
  "4.2": "",
  "−9.0": "",
  "Predicted score = 45 + 4.2(10) = 45 + 42 = 87. Residual = observed − predicted = 78 − 87 = −9.0. The negative residual means the student scored 9 points below the prediction.": "",
  "A researcher tests whether a coin is fair by flipping it 200 times and observing 115 heads. She uses a one-proportion z-test with H₀: p = 0.5 and Hₐ: p ≠ 0.5. She calculates z = (0.575 − 0.5)/√(0.5 × 0.5/200). What is the z-statistic?": "",
  "z ≈ 0.75": "",
  "z ≈ 2.12": "",
  "z ≈ 3.00": "",
  "z ≈ 1.50": "",
  "p-hat = 115/200 = 0.575. SE = √(0.5 × 0.5/200) = √(0.25/200) = √0.00125 ≈ 0.03536. z = (0.575 − 0.5)/0.03536 = 0.075/0.03536 ≈ 2.12.": "",
  "A school administrator compares SAT math scores between students who took an AP Statistics course and those who did not. AP group (n = 85): mean = 620, s = 75. Non-AP group (n = 120): mean = 580, s = 80. She constructs a 95% CI for the difference in means (AP − Non-AP) and gets (16.2, 63.8). What does this interval tell us?": "",
  "AP Statistics causes higher SAT scores": "",
  "We are 95% confident that AP Statistics students score between 16.2 and 63.8 points higher on SAT math than non-AP students, on average": "",
  "95% of AP students scored between 16.2 and 63.8 points higher": "",
  "There is no difference between the groups": "",
  "The interval (16.2, 63.8) does not contain 0, suggesting a significant difference. Since this is observational, we say 'associated with' rather than 'caused.' The CI quantifies the plausible size of the difference.": "",
  "An AP exam free-response question asks a student to design an experiment to test whether listening to music improves memory recall. Which design earns full credit?": "",
  "Survey students about whether they listen to music while studying and compare GPA groups after the fact": "",
  "Have all students listen to music and see if they remember more than their baseline performance level": "",
  "Let students choose whether to listen to music or not and compare average recall between the two groups": "",
  "Randomly assign 60 volunteers to two groups: one listens to music during a memorization task and the other works in silence. Both groups attempt to recall the same list. Compare mean recall scores using a two-sample t-test.": "",
  "A complete experimental design includes random assignment, a treatment (music), a control (silence), a response variable (recall score), and a statistical analysis plan.": "",
  "A student is told that a 99% CI is (12.1, 15.9) and a 95% CI from the same data is (12.5, 15.5). She is asked to explain why the 99% interval is wider. Which explanation is correct?": "",
  "Higher confidence requires a larger critical value (z* = 2.576 vs. 1.96), which increases the margin of error and produces a wider interval": "",
  "The 99% interval used a larger sample": "",
  "It is wider because the sample mean changed": "",
  "The 99% interval is wider because the standard error increased": "",
  "With the same data, increasing confidence from 95% to 99% requires a larger critical value, which widens the margin of error and thus the interval. There is a trade-off between confidence and precision.": "",
  "A comprehensive AP Statistics review problem: A factory produces bolts with a target diameter of 10.00 mm. A sample of 40 bolts has mean 10.08 mm and s = 0.15 mm. Test at α = 0.01 whether the mean diameter differs from 10.00 mm. The t-statistic is t = (10.08 − 10.00)/(0.15/√40). What is the t-value and what should the conclusion be, given that the two-tailed critical value for df = 39 at α = 0.01 is approximately ±2.71?": "",
  "t is approximately 3.37; fail to reject because 0.08 mm is a small difference that lacks practical significance": "",
  "t is approximately 5.33; reject the null hypothesis at all significance levels because the t-value is very large": "",
  "t is approximately 1.07; fail to reject the null hypothesis because the test statistic is below the critical value": "",
  "t ≈ 3.37; since |3.37| > 2.71, reject H₀. There is convincing evidence at the 1% level that the mean bolt diameter differs from 10.00 mm.": "",
  "SE = 0.15/√40 = 0.15/6.325 ≈ 0.02372. t = 0.08/0.02372 ≈ 3.37. Since |3.37| > 2.71, we reject H₀ at α = 0.01 and conclude the mean diameter significantly differs from 10.00 mm.": ""
